    {
        "content": "<p>(For 1 : it is just that you say this might be the only application of the CW-theorem for several polynomials )</p>",
        "id": 420893699,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1707661587
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh that's not what I meant. I meant this is the first application of CW, all versions included.</p>",
        "id": 420893765,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1707661648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, CW has a few classical applications!<br>\nOne of them is the proof that all finite fields are commutative (using the reduced norm), or to the theory of quadratic forms over finite fields (which are thus automatically isotropic in dimension <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>≥</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\geq3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">3</span></span></span></span>…)<br>\nThere are also combinatorical applications : how many hyperplanes are needed to cover the affine space over a finite field? and if you insist that these hyperplanes avoid the origin?<br>\nAnd applications in code theory.<br>\nMaybe more importantly, it relates the geometric properties of an algebraic variety with the presence of rational points, and is directly a motivation to quite fundamental questions in arithmetic geometry (papers by Ax, Katz, Esnault, Fakhruddin-Rajan…)</p>",
        "id": 420894465,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1707662219
    },
    {
